english:
  title: Record of the White Lotus Hermitage
  author: Yu Bang-seon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Wonmyeong, a wandering monk, came south and lodged his staff at Hwanggwi Temple in Yeongcheon for several years. Finding the grounds cramped and the village surroundings dreary, he sought a better place to dwell. With walking staff in hand, he wandered through many mountains until he reached Moja Peak in Andŭk County, where he discovered a sanctuary. Here the landscape lay deep and secluded, clear springs flowed over white stones, human traces were rare, and morning mists and evening vapors painted a thousand shifting moods—reminiscent of Mount Lushan's Fragrant Burner Peak. Delighted by this discovery, Wonmyeong began construction in the eighth month of Sinmyo, completing the work the following spring of Imjin. He named it the White Lotus Hermitage and asked me to compose this record.

    I have heard that the White Lotus Hermitage shuns ostentation. Its construction was modest—merely a Buddha hall adorned with earthen plaster, spotless as snow, with an image of Gautama hanging within for daily worship. Outside stands a small gallery for rest and contemplation. The design achieves sufficiency without excess; truly, this master knows the art of building.

    Imagine: when snow piles upon the courtyard, the monk sits veiled in meditation, facing the wall, oblivious to the cold that stings the skin. When moonlight floods the sleeping platform, he bares his chest to the night air, sips a single bowl of tea, and enters a state beyond desire—a man who has transcended worldly acclaim and found joy in emptiness. Surely such a one rivals Huiyuan of Mount Lushan. In the intervals of meditation, accompanied by two or three kindred spirits, staff in hand, they wander among clear springs and white stones—a scene a skilled painter could capture no less beautifully than the famous "Three Laughs of Lushan."

    Thus the monk found his dwelling, the dwelling found its form, the form found its name—is this not a confluence of fortune upon fortune? Yet I must say: in idle dwelling, discipline often grows thin, and the vigilance of body and mind may falter—a danger even we Confucians fear and guard against. But this master is different. Though he wears simple robes and eats plain fare, his heart remains fixed upon emptying illusions and delighting in the Way. Though he dwells apart from the world, his concern for his sovereign's longevity and his nation's welfare never wanes. He will not be seduced by the comfort of ease. Is this not admirable? This indeed deserves to be recorded.

    As for the scenic beauty of the mountains and the cost of construction—these are not matters the master wishes to boast of, nor would I presume to praise them. When spring breezes warm the rocks and ice thaws from the peaks, I shall take up my staff and walk there. Opening the bamboo window, leaning against the pine railing, gazing out beyond the eight horizons, I shall sweep away ten years of dust from my heart. Then, with one flourish of my brush, I shall write this record.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Huiyuan (慧遠, 334-416) was a celebrated Buddhist monk of Mount Lushan, known for his spiritual cultivation and the famous "Three Laughs of Lushan," a legendary gathering with the poet Tao Yuanming.
  - key: ''
    value: The "White Lotus" (白蓮) was a common name for Buddhist hermitages, symbolizing purity and enlightenment in Buddhist tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The eight horizons (八極) refer to the eight directions and extremities of the world in classical cosmology.
